POSITIVESELF: We just had our case manager changed over, just last week. So far, I have been very impressed with her willingness to look at services that can be applied to our family. Also with her ability to actually find the services that are needed...but, there really hasn't been a lot to go on. I am finding her to be a lot more helpful than the previous worker we had on the case. She does seem more willing to listen to our ideas on what our family needs. But I still don't feel like I'm getting any more help from her than we were getting with our previous workers. The one service that she has managed to find for us, to try to work into our family plan, is actually just a replacement service for one we had found on our own and that they refused to help us fund. I have been told that the reason for their refusal had something to do with the certification of the particular person we had found, I am finding that the the person they sent us to does not seem to be any more qualified than the person we found on our own.
POSITIVECHILD: Everytime that I talk to her, she seems to be in a hurry to get through our conversation and move on to another task and while I understand that she does have an extensive caseload, it's really frustrating for me to have to sum up what I'm trying to tell her in a very short time rather than actually being able to tell her everything I have to say. I would suggest that she try to spread out her appointmennts a little bit more, so she can spend more time with each client rather than fit in as many as possible in a very short time.
OPINION2: The only frustrating thing about the survey is that it was supposed to be specific to the most recent worker and since our worker had just recently changed, that didn't really give me a lot to go on. - which was frustrating. It would have made more sense to me to include the entire current experience with CPS, rather than just the most recent with a specific worker.

POSITIVESELF: i saw the caseworker last week when I went to my son's school meeting.  She was there and supportive of my decision to move my son back into kindergarten and she gave me a coucher for clothing for my children.  It seems like they are trying to help support me and get me and my family back on the right path.
POSITIVECHILD: I think they should have more resources available to the families.  The number one thing (suggestion) is that they (CPS) not keep switching the caseworkers, I've had 4.
ethnicity: Non-Hispanic, Black or African American Alone

POSITIVESELF: It's been pretty bad with my worker. My worker doesn't tell me what I need to do. My kid is depressed in foster care. My SW plays head games and is best friends with foster family.
POSITIVECHILD: She needs to be more helpful. Be more for the kid being with the mom and not in foster care.

POSITIVESELF: My experience was awful. I felt unheard, belittled, threatened, mis-labeled. The biggest one is that I felt not being heard or listened to. CPS always focused on the negative. They frustrated me.
POSITIVECHILD: My biggest suggestion is for them to take each person as an individual and to listen to them and not throw them in a horrible person category where they're unwilling to listen.
OPINION2: Basically CPS should look at each individual case and GET TO KNOW THE PEOPLE AND THE PROBLEMS AND THE SOLUTIONS BASED ON THE INDIVIDUAL NEEDS. Still I feel no one will listen to me. They have not taken the time to get to know me and see the mother that I am. They destroyed my family. I feel my daughter is going to suffer severe mental problems because of CPS. They do not care about the emotional distress they have put on my child. They were very destructive.

POSITIVESELF: I have mixed feelings.  I am gratful that I have been given the services I have been given.  I don't like that the courts had to get involved.  I feel like it was my husband that screwed up, not me.  I feel like I am cleaning up a mess that I didn't make.  Part of me wants to just go along with life and just be a mom and not have anyone judging what I am doing all the time.  I feel like I am under a micoscope.  Then again, I was already doing what they wanted me to be doing anyway.  It's not too bad, they arent't asking me to do something I'm not capable or anything like that.
POSITIVECHILD: She needs be more open to reality.  My CPS worker is new and doesn't have any children.  A lot og things were really over caitious, but she wasn't being realistic.  Listen to my suggestion more than just going with what the court says.  We need to work together and compromise to find a solution that works for everybody and still has the results the courts want.  I get concearned with the fact that my 2 year old son is not in my care.  Why am I allowed to have one and not two.  It is hard to watch him go back and forth.  It would be nice not to seperate the child from the parent unless it's threatning to the child's health.  I had custody before prison and now I don't and I don't really know why.  I'm just leaft wondering what's going on.

POSITIVESELF:
2 mo. ago there was a meeting where  CPS decided the fate of my children w/o any input of mine.  w/o communicating, they referred me to services that duplicated what I was already doing and were contrary to the ISSP.  We haven't recieved the referrals we were supposed to get.  Caseworker does not return phone calls/voicemail.  caseworker doesn't see improvements.  She is stuck on what originally happened and hasn't seen any of the positive changes that we've made - contrary to reports made by service providers.  They don't let the children see their step mother as much as me, which is not for the kids' best interest.  We have fulfilled our goals in individual counseling and parenting classes but our caseworker doesn't recognize these things.  It seems that the caseworker doesn't recognize our progress becuase the services weren't initiated by her, she wants us to start over with services she has referred us to.  

The department had done some good things, like providing counseling for our children and us.
POSITIVECHILD:
Needs to be more personal/case by case basis.  They need to get to know the families and not rely on their template and evaluations.  The clinical information can tell you about their tendencies, but doesn't tell you about the person.  D/f ppl. work in d'f ways.  I like to be engaged and understand how things work and how we get from A to B.  
My caseworker needs to follow through on the referrals that they are supposed to be making.  Needs to work towards the end goal and involve the parents in decision making.  Need to acknowledge the improvements made.

POSITIVESELF: I was mad because they said I could take my daughter into the community for visits, didn't let me. Social Worker didn't communicate with Guardian Ad Litem and me about visits. Social Worker went on vacation while my case was active and there was a lot to do. Investigation--CPS doctors testified that this is not an abuse or neglect case, they are keeping my daughter until I can learn to protect her better.
POSITIVECHILD: Let us know that we can get our kids back, give us better information about what needs to be done to get my kid back. Better communication about what specifically needs to be done to get my kid back. Better communication with everyone involved.
OPINION2: Glad we are doing the survey, hope it changes the system.

POSITIVESELF: Bad, because I was clean for 11 months, got my kids back after going through treament. My son was being abused by a foster parent. When I was in treatment I was depressed, wasn't learning anything in the services. They wouldn't help me access services and they do not have our best interests in mind, just what will cost them less. My son has been abused in foster care, so has my daughter. CPS basically forced me into dependency then took my kids away due to behavior problems. I relapsed in order to get housing. CPS has let my daughter fall through the cracks, she is now 8 months pregnant.
POSITIVECHILD: They need to go to school and learn about addiction and how it's a disease and generational. They need to know that it's not just a moral choice. The need to learn common sense.
OPINION2: I thought it was really helpful. If it would make a difference it would be great.

POSITIVESELF: My last contactg with CPS was very unacceptably rude.
POSITIVECHILD: Voice mail is  always full.  When I leave messages at the front desk, she does not recieve them.  Also I feel that I can never get a direct answer.  It is always I don't know.

POSITIVESELF: Horrible.  It isn't CPS that I deal with as much as the family dependency drug court.  The caseworker doesn't answer our questions.  I call her and she says she is too busy, and she doesn't return calls.  She never gives me a straight answer, only says "you know what you need to do."
POSITIVECHILD: To be more open and not to base every case off of the past ones she has dealt with.  LIsten to us because we are not all lying.  Some of us really do care about our children, and those of us who are doing the required services really do want to get better and get our children back.  We are not just another number, they have our children!

POSITIVESELF: she's not in it for the children, but for her own personal gain (job security).  they're not focused on helping families reunite.  they do not appear to care for anyone but themselves.  we keep getting the run around.  the sw we have does't follow thru, she's like to the judge, she's failed to send referrals for services we were court ordered to (parenting classes).
POSITIVECHILD: it took her getting suspended and her new boss making the referral during her absence for it to happen.  she tells us one thing, we go to do it, and then she gets upset with us for undermining her and going above her head.  she says one thing and does another.  she never keeps us informed; doesn't return phone calls..  she appears to be way over worked, can't get anything straight.

POSITIVESELF: we had a meeting and i walked out.  the reports they filed about me are untrue and unsubstantiated.  they are trying to get me to take services i do not need.
POSITIVECHILD: cps needs to see first hand what is happening and not rely on other peoples reports.

POSITIVESELF: Really bad. I think basically what happened I had my daughter taken away and they said that she was supposed to be back within the week b/c i'd gone to jail and i got out the same day and they didn't return her and instead kept her in foster in care, switched her around 4 foster cares and failed to tell me that and after 6 months that i had the choice to give up my rights or they're going to take them. I still don't have her.
POSITIVECHILD: Be more up front. There was a lot of things that happened that weren't said but were being done that weren't explained to me.
OPINION2: They suck.

POSITIVESELF: It was a bad experience. CPS just came and took my kids because of false reports made against me.
POSITIVECHILD: They should investigate more before they take kids out of the home and traumatize them even more. They need to be more upfront and socialize more with the parents instead of just going straight to the courts. They don't tell you anything and expect you to know everything yourself.

POSITIVESELF: I have a caseworker that I know at least twice has lied to me, because I've caught her. I haven't confronted her, there's no trust there. When I tried to be honest with her at our very first meeting, she has repeatedly used that honesty against me. When I first met her we were discussing discipline, and I told her we usually use time-out, unless its for a safety issue. If they run out in the street they're going to get a swat on the butt for that. And she says when they're in state care we can't use corporal punishment at all. Listen, we don't beat the kids. But if she says so, I won't do it, we don't have to spank them. I will be honest with you and tell you I don't agree with it, but I'm not going to break the rules. Ever since then she keeps bringing it up as something I haven't been compliant with.
POSITIVECHILD: The biggest one is if she's truly interested in what's best for my grandaughters, quit trying to disrupt their lives even more. Because apparently she's going to try and remove the kids from my care, which will be devestating for them. Absolutely devestating. And secondly, if she expects people to trust her, she needs to be honest.

POSITIVESELF: I got a call to come into the school because my niece made claims of sexual abuse by my ex-husband.  When i asked the social worker what was going to happen when this was found to be un-true, she said "don't worry, we'll make sure it's true".  My attorney told the worker she was not to contact me directly but she always went around the rules and contacted me anyway.  She was also officially sanctioned for not releasing my records to my attorney.  She was incredibly inappropriate with us.  It really felt like everything I did they tried to torn it around and use things against me.  I let them in my house, I did the things they wanted me to do. There is a new worker now and the case was closed almost immediately.  My children were never the issue-it was all about my niece and nephew who are now in foster care.
POSITIVECHILD: They need to follow the guidelines-don't harrass people, build trust by following the rules.  Follow the legal process, especially when someone has an attorney.  Communicate clearly and honestly with people.  Don't assume anything about people - who they are and what they did.  Work with us - I had nothing to hide and was open but I was treated as if I was guilty of something.
OPINION2: The survey is great.  I think it will be a useful tool to remind social workers that we're still people out here.

POSITIVESELF: Been involved for 1 year.  CPS involved because of meth use and got in fight with mother.  Up in the air right now - had daughter for past month but was taken away again when R was kicked out of treatment program (had been there for 4 months) - was near completion but got in trouble & had to stay longer, then got kicked out.  Feel that CPS has treated R well once R started following their rules, but it was difficult at first.  Have to be willing to do what CPS wants, or else it doesn't work.
POSITIVECHILD: understand that addiction is a disease and that people make mistakes - making mistakes shouldn't be the reason to lose your children.  if you're doing everything you should be doing, you shouldn't lose your children, even if it hasn't reached the one-year point (of program involvement/treatment).  don't threaten or hold out threats - offer help and support.
OPINION2: think that POC is doing a good thing and we know what we're doing, and we deserve a pat on the back.

POSITIVESELF: We had a very bad experience with CPS, it has ended ok.  CPS, first informed, promised daughter they would be here for her, but never came for 3 months.  I wrote a complaint to the office of asbudsmon for the way that CPS handeled this case.  I give credit to one CPS worker, LInda, who I think got fired or quit becasue I think, of my case.  She agreeed with us.  CPS never returns calls.   My opinion with CPS is that they thought they could raise my oldest daugherbetter than me and they stepped in and took her, and since then she has been on the run, addicted to drugs.  He said he could get down to her level, but she didn't listen.  They stormed in, tore apart the family and then finally dismissed the case.
POSITIVECHILD: Teenagers today are out of control, you cannot take their word, you have to check it out for yourself.  Take drug use into account, they will prob not be honest about it.
OPINION2: Family councling never received, they need to help put the family back.  I think survey is a good idea.  I hope it helps.  I have not seen the unifying that CPS claims they are all about.  Some families aren't corrupt, so they need to not be treated that way.

POSITIVESELF: I sent them a letter letting them know that I appreciate their help but I am not getting the help that I need now that I am in treatment.  They don't listen to what I need and are not offering me what I know is available to me.  I need more services and more help.
POSITIVECHILD: I need my caseworker to listen to me and offer me what I know they provide.

POSITIVESELF: CPS took my cousin's perspective and not mine. They take her word and don't use my side in front of the judge. They don't listen to me - I had a prior case dropped and they didn't listen to me that this case was the same situation.
POSITIVECHILD: To actually listen to my side and consider that there's something right about it and not just listen to other's side of the story.

POSITIVESELF: I don't feel that I am informed enough through the case manager or case worker. I'm not sure what the case manager's intentions are as far as whether they believe in reunification with my family or where they stand.
POSITIVECHILD: To be more communicative.
OPINION2: The survey is simple - its the way it needs to be...it's general - but it has to be to get a baseline.

POSITIVESELF: frustrating.  cps didn't fulfill promises of placement with child.  went into abhs and isabella house in order to be with child, but cps didn't place child w/R at isabella house, so R walked out after 5 weeks there. POSITIVESELF: The most recent one has been good.  Everything is going along reallysmoothly and I'm basically done with the program.  I'm ready for them to come home.  Things have gone by really fast and I feel very fortunate.  It has only been seven months and they are ready to come home.  But the experience I had before, just two months ago, was completely opposite.  The old caseworker expected me to fail.  I would complete something and she would immediately throw something else at me.  She talked down to me and expected me tjo fail.  She made me feel like a piece of crap.  I was in compliance the whole time but she didn't follow throough on what she said.  We had complaints about where my 2 year old was placed.  She put a child without special needs in a home specialized for children wiht special needs.  The worker said she did something about the many complaints but she never did.  Once I got the new caseworker she immediately got everything done.
POSITIVECHILD: I think that in my treatment program there are many other people involved in CPS.  People in compliance and doing what they are suppose to only want a pat on the back and some support to know that they are doing what you are suppose to do.  It goes much further than just expecting people to fail.  I also think they should try harder to keep siblings together.  I know it can be hard because there are speicalized programs for different groups, but they should try harder.  My two kids were seperated, and I know it is hard to help that from happening.  They put my teenager in a home for runaways, and she is n't a runaway--so she was treated badly because of my actions.  So I wish siblings could be placed together.
OPINION2: The older kids can understand what happens when they are taken from a home and can understand that there was drug use.  We aren't suppose to talk to the kids about our case, but I think that CPS should keep the kids informed.  I understand why parents shouldn't say anything, but someone should keep older kids informed about what is happening, the progess and non-progess, of the case.  It's not like she doesn't know what is going on, and it is her life!  I think that I should be able to meet face to face with the person taking care of my kid.  I don't need to know any specifics, and I understand the issues there, but we should have the right to at least meet one on one in the CPS office with the people who will care for our kids.  It would really help the depression.  There is one foster parents who keeps me informed when my kids are sick and  something happens, and that has meant the world to me to have an update.  You're in the dark unless they are kind enough to update us.

She actually believes what we are saying and she is dedicated.  She is in constant contact and informed.
POSITIVECHILD: Right now extreamely satisfied with how things are going.  My suggestion is that she not get wrapped up in the negative entity in how they look at parents and since she is new I hope she stays open minded.  With CPS, one person says one thing and they automatically jump on it without investigating.  I don't want her to get caught in the old ways.  It really affects the parents when they come into the home and take their children.  I recognize there are children that need it.  They look at people as a number and not as a person.  Train workers to recognize truth from fiction.  There is so much training that they should have that they don't have.  Another suggestion is to have less cases per case worker.  (R recognizes the government as being the cause of many of the problems).  I feel it is a really big test as in "Who is ready to be a parent and who isn't"
OPINION2: Our situation has been really hard.  We have been on the other side of things and this time a lot things were taken out of context and cut and pasted.  They were inaccurate.  My fiancees mother (that works as a juvienile caseworker) was horrified at how her words were taken out of context.  Lots of things in our file was totally wrong.  I was proactive in getting my son help and it was turned around on me.  I was so happy to hear about this program.  They can come in and rip your family apart.  I really do hope that things change in the system.  There are a lot things they take way to far.  It should be beyond a shadow of a doubt and complete evidence.  Not just hearsay. We see so many people being angry and being reactive and not proactive.  Our suggestion is for all parents to go through parent classes one per year. (At this point the fiancee stepped and told his part. Biggest complaint is that not everyone is on the same page).  Both stated that they are discriminated against for being low-income.

POSITIVESELF: my son who has a mental health disability is the one who got cps involved. he reported a dime sized bruise on his bottom and said that his grandfather had hit him. so the police were called down to his school my sister went over there and told them what the real story was..that my son has been the one attacking us. So that cps worker came and closed the case and called another worker to help with my son who was on his 5th hospitalization. this cps worker was supposed to help us with placement with my son for residential treatment because the hospital was stating that he needs 24hr professional care. instead of doing that, they first offered foster care, then she never called when she was supposed to. the worker and the rest of the staff were planning on placing him with his father, who had been removed from the home by the police for threatening our son.  my worker came here, and she lectured me about how I should believe that people can change. I was just trying to protect my children from being harmed.
POSITIVECHILD: i don't think she has been exposed to very many mentally disturbed people. there should be some system in place for my worker to go above the heads of her superiors for special circumstances like ours. she cancelled his ssi which cancelled his medical. she had no idea that his ssi was connected to his medical.the best thing that they could do is connect the services better so that the left hand knows what the right hand is doing.

POSITIVESELF: A rollercoaster - that's the best way to put it.  Just a series of ups and downs, promises made but not fulfilled, told one thing but then informed that CPS has changed its mind or that there are a couple of further hoops to jump through before CPS does what it has promised to do.  Frustrating experience.  Feel that CPS has blown the whole situation (of R's involvement) out of proportion - and this feeling is shared by other providers familiar with the situation as well.
POSITIVECHILD: To do spot home visits, including showing up unannounced to see what's going on and see what everybody's doing, including whether they are doing what they should be doing or are doing what they shouldn't be doing.  Also, try to be a little more down to earth and able to relate to people - current CPS worker is an ex-parole officer and isn't very gentle or able to relate to families.  With most recent worker, it's been a little difficult to keep in touch because W has been doing academy training - so next time, please make sure that someone has completed training or that the replacement person is fully up-to-speed with the case and able to take action in the other worker's absence.  Also, if W is going to be in training or unavailable, then provide an emergency contact number (e.g. a visit nearly fell through because W was out of town and didn't leave a number).
OPINION2: Nothing negative - actually went quite well and was positive experience.  Not uncomfortable with questions or answering them.

POSITIVESELF: It was okay, but I am having problems with getting my bed date into treatment (it is one of my requirements for getting my kids back). I have been on the list for 3 months and have expressed this to my social worker and she is just busy, I guess. Other than that, she has been good - she is hard to get ahold of a lot, though.
POSITIVECHILD: That if you tell the client to call you and if you leave a message and you'll return their call - and they leave a message and you don't return their call - even after repeated messages..... I guess, check your messages more.
OPINION2: It was actually pretty good.

POSITIVESELF: They made up a lot of lies and embellished stories w/o looking at the factual evidence. They repeatedly harrassed me. They never listened to us. One of the CPS workers told me I was a bad mom and that I didn't deserve my children & that they were going to make sure your children were placed with someone else. They sat up on the stand in court and lied and got caught in lies numerous times (which is why my children are home now and the case is closed). They really need a lot of restructuring. They don't want my family back together again. I thought their job was to try to reunite families, instead they threaten that if my ex is in my life, they will remove my children - even though we have both gotten services. They fact that they are saying he can't be apart of his son's life makes me angry - its not fair. They have a lot bigger fish to fry. I wish they could just be proud that they have one out of several hundred that is a success story instead of looking for some fault there.
POSITIVECHILD: I think that they need to be retrained. Stop looking at everybody like they are all bad, or thinking that every case is identitcal or that someone is lying about something always. They also need to stop taking these cases so personally.
OPINION2: I think it was cool - I haven't been able to actually talk with someone about my experiences!

POSITIVESELF: Very unhelpful, stressful.  They didn't provide visitation, so I had to go back to court in contempt in order to get visitation with my children. My case worker was very arguementative towards me, and would cut me off.  She always had excuses.  I called and made a report to CPS when my children were living with their father and being left home alone and when my daughter needed an abscessed tooth removed that wasn't being taken care of and CPS swept it under the rug.  CPS placed my  kids into a home without investigating it and making sure it was a safe environment  and to this day, CPS still hasn't been to the home where my kids are at (their father's place).

Because the father has my kids, my caseworker told me that whatever he says goes --- I think she should have had a different attitude. POSITIVESELF: It was a nightmare.  They made alot of assumptions about us as people and as parents without having any understanding of disabilities (our kids' or ours (both of us have Aspergers).  They labeled me as "uncaring" or "unemotional" without considering that as a characteristic of my Aspergers.  They also had no understanding of the potentially destrctive behavior of kids with autism - so they would not believe the degree of destruction in the house that was caused by our 4 year old.  Then somehow they seem to think that taking the kids away would "cure" the autism.  the lack of understanding of the impact of disabilities on all family members was astaounding.   Now we don't have out kids at home. there is NO plan in place and we have had little to no communication with our worker.
POSITIVECHILD: Make sure they all have autism training that extends beyond infancy.  Tey need to understand it in early childhood, later childhood into adulthood.  The typical parenting styles just don't work and they need to understand that.  In 4 months since they took the kids, we have heard pretty much nothing about what we need to do to work things out, get our kids back, anything.  My advice...communicate openly and frequently; don't assume parents know what's happening or what they have to do.  Put things in writing.  Don't offer help unless you can actually give it!!  We have been all but begging for help for over 5 years...no one has offered us any resources other than ones we already had.
OPINION2: The questions seem skewed towards children who do NOT have disabilities; it is hard to feel like i am answering the questions accurately because my kids' disabilities do alter the way I need to parent.  I don't fall into the mold of the "typical" parent.

POSITIVESELF: I work with them everyday. My experience is that they tell me the goal is to reunite me with my daughter, but I feel sometimes they are working against me more than not. So, all that time I put into those 31 other groups became meaningless to them and just down the toilet, that was very upsetting.
POSITIVECHILD: CPS  treats every case the same, we all have supervised visits, and slow return. I think every case when it comes to the return process should be done differently.

POSITIVESELF:
I don't believe that I would be getting my kids back as soon as I am if I wouldn't have bent to the CPS schedule.  I have been to everything and have volunteered to do 2 visits/wk in order to get it going faster -- but this has been a financial burden for me because of all the work I have had to miss.  I don't think it is right for families that are really trying to be so financially burdened by CPS' timeline/schedule.  
CPS should try harder to keep siblings together.  
When they are returning children home, usually not all of the children are returned at the same time and I think this is really hard on the kids if they all don't return at the same time because they may not understand the reasons why.
POSITIVECHILD:
From the beginning, CPS wasn't quick enough to get services going. ie, parenting classes were beginning, I had to keep bugging my caseworker for the referral! Also, I had to prove that I was clean for 60 days, but it wasn't until 40 days after my inital UA that CPS finally got me set up on the color system.  Another thing that wasn't handled right, my 10 yr. old son was sent to counseling by himself and the counselor later said he didn't need it anymore -- but that's because a child can't tell what's really happening. an adult needs to be there.  Also, it's not right when parents aren't  informed about their children while they're in foster care (ie: school reports, doctor visits, etc).  
also, it will be a more difficult transition for my children to come home from foster care because they are now used to being able to do more (like skating ea. fri.).  I am a single mom, I don't have a lot of $ and there are no extras.  I think they should try and keep the foster home similar to the real home.

POSITIVESELF: It was frustrating, it was confusing, and really the emphasis is that we have parents lilke us who have never known anyone who has been in the process.  I ask lots of questions and the answers taht we receive and assistance we don't get has been minimal and poor.  I think the issue is that they assume that you know what the process is and the requirements are and as an example when I asked for some sort of written pamphlet that gave me driection on how to select supervisors .  I asked multiple times and never got it and as it was I had to ask specific questions and they didn't take the time to educate and be proactive about helping us.  It would be good if they said "you are at this point in the process, here's what you need, here are your resources" rathern than "oh, you didn't do that right.  We get penalized when we just didn't know up front.  We try to do things right but we don't know what "right" is.
POSITIVECHILD: To be responsive, respectful, not condescending.  Try to be empathetic in terms of who theya re dealing with and the circumstances of the case and the backgrounds of the parents they work with.  Put yourself in the families' shoes.  The condescending part - it's important that we aren't talked down to.  It's respect and accountability from the CPS worker perspective.       Be upfront and take the initiative in letting people know what they have to do.  We just didn't know stuff and then got threatened and chastised.  My intent was to follow stuff and protect my kids.
OPINION2: When our kids were first taken and the police were there CPS took  my oldest child, who has a severe peanut allergy, I gave him snacks he could eat but they fed him peanut butter cookies and  he had an allergic response.  This is an example - they should have asked us "is there anything we need to be concerned about or know about your child"  When they put him in the caregiver's home, straight from the hospital, they gave no instructions to them on how to put his brace on, how to give his meds.  Just like dropping off a puppy or something.  They need to be proactive and accountable.       In the meeting after my children were taken, the caregiver brought it up because no medical info was obtained, the social worker looked at R and blamed her for not telling them when the children were taken (when they were taken, it was a very emotional moment for parent and children). This was my frist meeting with them and I was shocked to learn that CPS had no accountability for slip ups like this.

POSITIVESELF: We're on our second round here-we had custody of my grandaughter for 3 years the first time. That was April; by June he was drinking again.  In October I went and picked up my grand daughter - he was passed out, there were drugs and alcohol in the house & she was alone in the house.  It seems like CPS is just going to repeat the same steps of giving my son custody again before he is ready, by not asking him to prove he can be a responsible parent while his daushgter is safely living with us. They need to be more creative and open to finding good solutions for individual cases.

POSITIVESELF: CPS was great, but when they turned it over to Family Reconciliation Services, the experience couldn't have been worse.  The FRS counselor was terrible - if this was a reconciliation counselor, I'd hate to see what a take-away was.  Biggest suggestions were a book, a parenting class, and join a support group.  Had a family team meeting before FRS got involved, and everyone agreed.  FRS counselor disagreed, told R that R needed to accept responsibilities as a parent and bring R's child-in-care home. R's child had been assigned a team child atty, who had contact w/AAG, which resulted in getting an atty, which is what helped.  No real help available from state for teens.  Get adoption support & counseling, but anything bigger the state doesn't do anything - placements or other involvement.  FRS counselor had a bad reputation amongst other counselors and was so unhelpful that supervisors agreed & R turned down all other state services to get away from FRS.
POSITIVECHILD:
R paid for behavioral placement in OR themselves for 9 months; it did no good.  Finally got to feeling that WA needed to help out.  State didn't properly inform about adopted children (they were FAS); R probably wouldn't have adopted them because of concerns about R's own patience and parenting. Ultimately had to let state file a dependency so WA would provide whatever R's child needs until 18 because R afraid that state would back out if they only did a temporary placement.  If R had an W that really wanted to work with R's family, it wouldn't have cost thousands in fees and it wouldn't have been such a struggle.  Everybody in system says state doesn't provide services and doesn't want to do BRS referral.  Also, state wants to charge parents support.

FRS W shouldn't be in her job and should display more skill and better attitude.
OPINION2:
W should have been removed from case, and was supposed to.  W told others that R was just trying to get rid of R's son - told this to residential centers, told R's husband that R was confused, overly emotional, and nuts.  W wouldnt return calls, would direct information in strange ways, etc.

Research protocols are persistent, but it's actually appreciated.  Also, many questions just didn't apply to R.

Curious to see what changes will be implemented, if any, as a result of the study & intervention.  If survey helps it happen, that's great.  But not holding breath after 14 years in the system w/adopted children.  As a rule, most workers have been great and helpful, even if hands tied.  Unfortunately, the FRS W was the first really bad experience.
